Title: THE 5TH WAVE - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
Wasn't a terrible film, but at the risk of the generic _"suddenly everyone is a movie critic (nerg nerg nerrrg!)"_ line of defense, I got to say, it sadly got a little... dumb around the halfway point.
I was totally into the premise of apocalyptic survival, as your traveling group of people you care about, slowly dwindles away, to a staggering, lonely solo quest, where everything is out to get you and felt the build-up was leading the film elsewhere, but the whole "I choose love!!" interspecie love-triangle was completely unnecessary. I have no gripe with "Evan Walker", but I just didn't feel it.
The idea of the "5th wave" was honestly really good and pretty alarming to think about, but the execution was a bit... meh?
Had a little bit of _"Ender's Game"_ feel to it; Kids "playing video games" _BUT!!_ "in real life"...

Comment:
I want to warn people away from this, it is terrible on all fronts. I am not sure why Netflix continues to output these terrible scifi movies, maybe it is too fuel American fears of invasion and the need to weaponize suburbia. 

Some annoying elements are: 
The all-american blonde girl as lead and narrating a dystopian future is completely ridiculous - there's a reason why Morgan Freeman got all the narration jobs, because it's important to the tone of the film, requires craft and a cadence in the narrators voice. 
The acting is terrible (just wait till the Goth girl joins the unit).
The human interactions are given so little attention yet we are to believe the forced love story, the unfailing love for the brother, the main character's mental toughness. 
The plot is awful. The child soldiers make no sense to any alien plan. Go watch Dark, also on Netflix, for a good scifi story.

Title: THE 5TH WAVE - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
SPOILERS AHEAD/ RANT:

As a fan of the book serious the movie got barley a fraction of anything in the book correct. When I read the book, it was gritty; super bloody, very  dark setting and lots of emotion. Almost had a zombie apocalypse vibe to it. When I saw the movie, all I got with a typical teen romance knock off of 'The Host'. The movie was good in terms of cast, not really for Evan tho, but like seriously the movie made me so sad because it was supposed to be a two hour rated r flick about a girl in the apocalypse trying to get her brother back from an alien infested army training kids to exterminate their own race. Some times I just watch the movie thinking about why could have been an awesome and fresh take instead of romance. In the book there was literally only two pages that dealt with romance. The story didn't focus on romance, but Cassie being alone and trying to do whatever it take to find her brother. The movie made it all about the romance, when that was only a small part of it. Plus they took out the BEST scenes of the book. I didn't expect the movie to be 100% like the book but it was only like 45% like the book.

This series was so amazing and it's just sad to see Hollywood cater to romance driven teens who can't appreciate something that doesn't have to fully deal with romance. The same with the hobbit, like yes we loved he romance but did we NEED it? 

Idk, I respect everyone's opinions but this movie was a huge opportunity wasted. That being said, the cast was really put together well, but everything else was meh and made to be cliche.

Comment:
ALRIGHT, HONEST & POSITIVE REVIEW:
I'd give this movie around an 8.3 (lowest) - 8.9 (highest)
It was actually really good. While watching it I got goosebumps & even cried during a few scenes. I think the reason most people look down upon this movie is because 
1. they probably read the book before the movie. And for almost every case where that happens, people who read the book first tend to hate the movie. (so if you haven't read the book yet, I really do recommend you to give this movie a chance)
2. Yes, some scenes were cliche: mostly scenes of cassie and evin. But what do you expect? most romantic scenes are cliche.
3. Some actors couldnt play their roles well. For example, Cassies father didnt quit fit his role. Her brother too, but you cant blame him considering hes just a kid (probably 8 years old?)
4. Unfortuantely, it does end with a BIT of a cliffhanger. 
5. Most people read too many negative reviews before watching the movie & therefore do not enjoy the movie as much. you get me? as in, people follow the crowd. If one person says the movie sucked, everyone will too.

Okay so in conclusion (!!!!) i REALLY do recommend everyone to watch this movie. Do not look at too many reviews before watching it because it WILL effect your views on watching the movie. While me and my siblings were watching it, none of us understood why it got so many reviews. It was great and i definitely would watch it again.

Anyone else who watched this movie after reading my advice:
please reply with what you thought about the movie & if you agree to let anyone else who's skimming through the comment know whether what i said was legit or now (:

Comment:
I think the film was very good! It really showed the huge impact the aliens had on humanity. 
First killing all electricity (one of the biggest things we survive on now days), 
2nd earth quakes and floods
3rd virus
4th humanised aliens.

The 5th wave to be honest made no sense however. I did not get what the 5th wave was? The army of human children?? 

Overall the film was really good, showing how huge the impact was! The scenery was also done very well with all the abandoned cars and buildings. 

But the ending was probably one of the worst endings I've seen. (Ok sure it is meant to lead to a sequel film like other films), but it was left WAY to open! 
What happens to the surviving humans? Does the humanised aliens get stopped? What happens to their alien friend? Ect... .. .
Also other questions I have is that the aliens had been flying across earth for a week before electricity got killed off. What the heck was the military, navy and armies of earth doing during that time???

Comment: Not to provoke the usual petulant YouTube altercation, but I just read the two Yancey books a few weeks ago, and went to see the film when it opened, and have seen it again since, and, for my tastes(and we all know the old saying, "concerning taste, there's no dispute") I thought the filmmakers did an excellent job in adapting an at times confusing story line in the making of this film.¬† The books were real page-turners and, for young-person's novels, a bit challenging to follow since the narration changed with each section with a different character telling the story----to literally adapt the manner of story-telling for a film would take several TV seasons.¬† From the Hunger Games to the Giver to the Divergent series to the 5th Wave books and movie, I have always enjoyed these post-apocalyptic, dystopian stories.¬† I'm reasonably certain that---with box office receipts being what they are---this will not be a film trilogy:¬† that's too bad since Chloe Grace Moretz is a most versatile and engaging young actress, and the rest of the story deserves a celluloid retelling.¬† I'm sure I'll get when it comes on DVD, and will read the final installment of the books when it gets published this spring.

Title: THE 5TH WAVE - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
After watching the film, I would simply rate this movie as a simple four out of ten; the romance was forced between Evan and Cassidy, I wanted to cringe when said romantic interactions took place. Didn‚Äôt feel like a romance, not much of a build-up, not much of a foundation for the two to fall in love together I guess? Felt more one-sided really, Evan was pining, and Cassidy was just indifferent. I did like the little nicknames the others had in the squad; almost discarding themselves as human beings, and fitting themselves into that archetype of a solider, going by the names on the field. The army introduction was interesting, I was more interested in this side than Cassidy‚Äôs side, I wish there was more screen time focused on flushing this aspect out, and working more towards the reveal, felt rather.. underwhelmed when Zombie figures it out? 

And the others; more information on the others would be nice, and the whole using the kids plot needed more of a backing point, More perspective to really hone on this aspect, otherwise, initially, what is the point? You can do all this, but you need kids, human kids to wipe out the rest of humanity?  So yeah 4/10 for me.

Comment:
Another example of a trailer revealing too much of the movie, thus hurting its reception?

I have not seen this yet, but from just watching the trailer, I feel like I basically saw the whole movie. It is called the 5th wave, and waves 1-5 were all revealed. I am annoyed that I saw this trailer because I feel like it just crushed any chance I had of being intrigued. There is probably not much mystery left which leaves what appears to be some kind of teen romance.  So I am going to give this movie a shot while trying to imagine how I would feel about it if I did not know what each wave brought. I'll post an update to reveal if I think the movie is just terrible or if the revealing nature of the trailer hurt the movie's ability to be entertaining.

The reason why it sets in a perspective of a girl or a teenage guy, whatever, is to grab the attention of the growing population of the younger audience. Plus, people now a days have the lowest attention spans (but no one is trying to throw shots, so please no caps lock). 

Also, I have not read the book, but looking through the comments the people who did read it say that it was very well written. There wasn't any love scene (least not a lot) but its used to make the common man watch it. (this is how Fifty Shades and Twilight got popular). Some books turned to movies suffer, like The Giver, because it was just a fresher 1984 pretty much. (though the book was better as I have heard and researched).

Hollywood will only cater to the "short attention span people" and not the people who actually want accurate in the book because lets face it those "less minded people" are out there more in the world. Its why reality shows keep getting worse. So, before you jump to anything think before you slam your fingers into the keyboard. Give some things a chance and not jump to conclusion. THINK.

That is all, enjoy the rest of your day/night.

Comment: I'll be the first geek to point out that airplanes don't fall out of the sky even if they have all engines fail simultaneously. The only thing that would cause an attitude like that in the trailer is a low-speed stall (like Air France 447), and that's usually pilot error. If the idea behind the scene is aliens robbed everything of power, an a340 or 747 (or any other jet) can glide for 90 miles and usually make a safe landing from cruise altitude, even with no power. In real life, it's running out of fuel, not aliens, that usually causes all the engines to quit, and in most of those cases the plane landed "safely" (though not without white knuckles) Sure it's a great film though:)
